6:30 - 7:00 Participants arrive and socialize. 

7:00 - 7:15 Group introductions and announcements from participants and organizers.

7:15 - 9:15 Hacking. Project teams break out to work.  New participants can join teams, circulate, or seek out the Co-Captains for orientation (Justin, Matt, or Leah).

~7:30 Food delivered. 

9:15 - 9:30 Everyone reconvenes and shares reactions to and progress made over the last two hours. Show and tell if time/resources allow it. Thank you and goodnight.

9:30 Sometimes an after party (Happy Hour)

Notes: 

• Text Matt 202-330-1154 or Justin at 301-538-5812 for entry if no one is at the door.

• Bring cash for food and drink! Pay what you can.

If you are new to Code for DC… 

• Bring a laptop if you can (it’s ok if you can’t) 

• Take a look at our active projects

• Review the Code for DC Code of Conduct

• Check out our Getting Started Guide https://github.com/codefordc/getting-started

• Start working on a project with someone or bring your own project


• Introduce yourself to others

• If you had a good time join Google Group and Meetup

**Please RSVP here so we know what GDI members are attending, but you MUST register through the Tech The Halls Eventbrite page found here.  If you do not have an Eventbrite ticket, you are not registered for the event.  Make sure to use promo code GDITTH15 for 15% off!** 



Come in from the cold, grab a drink and kick off the holiday season with a bang!

Please join us as we celebrate all of the reasons DC is a tech mecca, Wednesday, December 3rd for the 3rd annual DC Web Women's Tech The Halls 2014 Holiday Party presented by Adobe!  

Tech The Halls! is a celebration that brings together local and national tech groups as one community for the DC area. DCWW, Girl Develop It DC, UXPA-DC, STC WDC,Web Mavens, Reaching Latinos Online, Color of Tech, NAMDE and technologists from all over the DC-Metro area will meet, share ideas and network.

Held at the chic Capitale in downtown Washington, DC, Tech the Halls provides an opportunity for entrepreneurs, startups, designers, developers, coders and strategists to unify, network, and learn more about changing technology trends and best practices, as well as promoting the important role we play in the burgeoning tech economy.

There will be an open bar, unlimited food, and music by DJ Clinton Matthews!!

Attendees will receive a holiday tech-themed gift bag (quantities limited), and a chance to win tech/non-tech prizes including a very special grand prize!

As always, men are encouraged to attend any DCWW event!

Twitter hashtag: #techthehalls2014

Interested in sponsoring Tech The Halls? please contact us at [masked] or visit our sponsorships page.

General event questions? Please contact [masked].

**Last day to receive a refund is Wednesday, November 26th 2014. After 11/26/14 all ticket sales are final.

other.description:
CaBi Hack Night is a show & tell of apps and data visualizations about Capital Bikeshare. Read about CaBi Hack Night I and CaBi Hack Night II to get an idea of how it works. Got a cool CaBi project? We'd love to see it!

Doors open at 6:00, with food courtesy of our sponsor Twilio. The presentations start at 6:30. Note our location this month is in DC, at WeWork's beautiful space at the Wonder Bread Factory. Thank you WeWork for hosting us!

Our awesome speakers are:

• Colin Hughes of the Institute for Transportation and Development Policy will talk about planning principles for bikeshare systems.

• Trevor Gerhardt will show us a dcjs data explorer for CaBi.

• Mathias Hansen will show us how he visualizes an individual's trip histories with his Trip statistics app.

• Paul DeMaio, program manager of Arlington's CaBi service, will share a study on CaBi’s first-mile/last-mile ridership.

• Zach Rausnitz will show us Bikeshare IQ.


• Erek Dyskant of BlueLabs will show us a directed graph of CaBi trips that studies neighborhood clusters.


• Matt Conway will present research on how bikeshare station popularity is connected to the stations' accessibility to residences, jobs, and neighborhood amenities.


As always, stay tuned to @techiesdc for updates. Our hashtag is #cabihacknight.
other.name: CaBi Hack Night III

other.description:
Hack and Tell will be at WeWork Chinatown again in December! (Hooray!) Everyone is looking forward to hearing about *your* cool hack! Presentation signups are here:

http://bit.ly/presentatdc

The format is informal, engaging, and friendly: presenters have 5 minutes to show off their hack (it goes faster than you’d expect) and then the audience has 5 minutes to ask questions, make jokes, and suggest ideas and feedback. The hacks that people present are anything from how to train your dog to text you when it needs a walk to [something more serious... like inverted circuit wallpaper]. Show us what you’ve got! But remember: no startup pitches, dull work projects, no deckware!

If you’re interested in presenting, complete this short form to let us know: http://bit.ly/presentatdc

See you at the meetup! We'll start close to seven. There may be a couple beers. It's going to be fun! :) Big thanks to WeWork for hosting us! We love WeWork! We love you! We love hacks! <3
other.name: Round 15: Probably Hoverboards

other.description:
Hiring the right person can be hard. Come join us in December to hear how data science can help staff your next dream team.

Agenda

6:30 PM -- Networking & Food 

6:55 PM -- Greetings & Prizes

7:00 PM -- Transforming Labor Markets: Applying Data Science and Predictive Analytics to Hiring and Team Assembly - Myra Norton

9:00 PM -- Post event drinks at Green Turtle

Location

Google maps does a good job of pinpointing the exact building location based on the address above.

Parking is not an issue. You can park on the street nearby or you can take up any Visitor spot that you can find. Also, feel free to park in the Ad.com/AOL employee parking lot but not in spaces marked Under Armour or Reserved.

Talk

Transforming Labor Markets: Applying Data Science and Predictive Analytics to Hiring and Team Assembly

This talk will provide an overview of the rapidly growing but still small industry of applying emerging data techniques to hiring and team assembly. It will cover the methods used and results achieved in several verticals—healthcare and long term care, application development, and business process outsourcing. The session will cover the strengths and weaknesses of different techniques, and will outline specific outcomes and adoption challenges from several enterprise case studies. We will also discuss the opportunities uncovered by these techniques, where the industry is headed, and how rapidly evolving technology and regulatory developments are likely 
to affect those opportunities.

Speakers

Myra Norton
 President and COO
Myra Norton joined Pegged Software in November of 2012 after a rich career in data and analytics. Norton accumulated extensive academic experience as an administrator in the College of Science and Technology at Temple University, teaching in the Business School and the College of Science and Technology at Temple University, and lecturing on mathematics and statistics at Towson University while providing academic support to midshipmen at the United States Naval Academy. 

A leading thinker on the application of analytics to Big Data, she has been speaking and writing on this subject in a variety of venues: as a speaker and facilitator for the Network Roundtable at the University of Virginia, the Chief Marketing Officer (CMO) Council, the Council for the Advancement and Support of Education (CASE), the Business Marketing Association (BMA). She has worked with researchers from Harvard University, Babson College, University of Virginia, NIH, University of Maryland, and the University of Chicago. She leads the National Girls Collaborative Project as part of her work with the Center for Women in Technology, is currently serving as a member and immediate past chair of the Industrial Advisory Board for the College of Engineering and Information Technology at UMBC, serves as a mentor for college students and young professionals in the Baltimore area, and works with high school students through the National Foundation for Teaching Entrepreneurship (NFTE). Norton graduated from the University of Alabama with a BS in Math Education and received an MA in Mathematics and an MS in Statistics at Temple University.

Post-event Drinks

Green Turtle 

1606 Whetstone Way

Baltimore, MD 21230

For two intensive days, we’ll put you face to face with the world’s foremost industry experts to teach you the the latest methods, tools, and best practices for the industry's most important development platforms.

December 12: Morning Breakout Sessions, Afternoon Keynotes, Closing Reception, Sponsor Gallery

For details on speakers, schedule, and more please visit the ModevCon website!

other.description:
For December's Data Science DC, we're very happy to have Dr. Regina Nuzzo from Gallaudet University discuss a fundamental, but flawed, tool of statistical inference and statistical communication, the p-value. Expect a very... significant... presentation.

Agenda:

• 6:30pm -- Networking, Empenadas, and Refreshments

• 7:00pm -- Introduction, Announcements, Give-aways

• 7:15pm -- Presentation and Discussion

• 8:30pm -- Data Drinks (Tonic, 2036 G St NW)

Abstract:

What's the fuss around the p-value? This standard measure been widely canonized -- from entry-level statistics texts all the way to regulatory agencies and the scientific publication system -- yet also often misunderstood, misapplied, and obsessively stalked. In this talk, Dr. Nuzzo will discuss misleading interpretations and puzzling paradoxes that can result from statements of statistical significance, present some of the latest thinking about teasing out certainty and evidence in data, and discuss the most interesting philosophical and practical trends to look for on the horizon.

Bio:

Dr. Regina Nuzzo is a freelance science journalist and professor at Gallaudet University. She received her Ph.D. in statistics from Stanford University, post-doctoral training in the Music Cognition Lab at McGill University, and graduate science journalism training at University of California, Santa Cruz. Her writings about data, probability, and statistics have been published in Nature, Science News, Biomedical Computation Review, and Scientific American. Her Nature feature article about the p-value recently won the American Statistical Association’s 2014 Excellence in Statistical Reporting Award. Follow her on Twitter @ReginaNuzzo.

Sponsors:

This event is sponsored by the GWU Department of Decision Sciences, Pearson/InformIT, Statistics.com, LivingSocial, Novetta Solutions, Elder Research, and Five 9 Group.
other.name: Problems with the p-value

Because this will be held via Hangouts On Air, it is vital that you have everything installed before the class starts. Installation instructions will be made available before the class. If you have any problems, ping us!

Things you need to have installed:

• Python (2.7+)


• pip (we use it to install Flask)


• Flask

• Git (for accessing the class materials)

Here is the link for the class. You won't see much until the class starts.

other.description:
Welcome to the wonderful world of traffic, driving, and parking!

Doors open at 6:00 with pizza and drinks, and the presentations start at 6:30. 


• Nikola Ivanov of CATT Lab will present "Real-World Problems, Real-World Solutions," talking about probe vehicle data analytics, and showing us the Regional Integrated Transportation Information System (RITIS).

• Van Standifer will show us Flexspot, an app he developed in Georgetown University to create a market for private parking spaces.


• ParkingPanda will talk about their app that lets drivers reserve parking in advance.


• The folks at Metropia will talk about their vision to connect commuters, businesses, employers and government agencies to drive improvements in metro mobility.

• Matthew George of Bridj will tell us how they are how they're makes cities smarter by crunching millions of data points to see how people are traveling throughout the city.


Do you have an auto-centric app or data viz? Sign up to present by contacting Michael. 

Follow @techiesdc for "Transportation Techies" updates.

other.name: Autotopia Night

other.description:
With the diverse skills and interests of our group, let's explore how the experience in our backgrounds plays into our tech careers. Then, let's get practical and walk through how to launch a web app. For January, a tech founder will share the intersection of her subject matter expertise with tech, discussing how localization (fitting a site or piece of software to a culture, often including language) interacts with design and development. Then, one of our web dev members will show us the simple steps to deploy a web app.

Terena Bell is CEO of In Every Language. She sits on the White House Business Roundtable and writes a monthly column for MultiLingual Magazine on the impact of societal macroforces on the translation industry. Terena is former Secretary of the Globalization and Localization Association (GALA) and a former Association of Language Companies (ALC) board member. She tweets as @InEveryLanguage.

Say the word "language" in tech circles, and people think Python or Ruby. But what about Urdu or Arabic? Since both these--as well as many others--read right to left, not thinking about foreign language now can lead to user interface and other development problems down the road. And that's just the beginning. Not only should (foreign) language impact HOW you design, but WHAT you design as globalization creates the need for more and more multilingual and translation apps. From idea to execution, Terena Bell, CEO of In Every Language, shows you why foreign languages are just as essential to today's developer as coding languages are.

Mandy Moore is a Junior Developer at Mobility Labs and a recent graduate of General Assembly's Web Development Immersive program.  In her talk she'll show you how you can share your projects with the world for free by deploying to Heroku using Git.  Basic knowledge of Git, a free Heroku account and a small project to deploy will be helpful but not required.

If you're considering joining, please read our rules, to determine if this group is right for you:

http://www.meetup.com/Ladies-Who-Code-Washington-DC/about/

There will be two 30-45 minute sessions + open discussion and Q&A. Tech topics will be selected soon. Watch this page for details.


You are encouraged to bring your projects, ask for help on any tech related topic, or just chill and enjoy the event.


If you're considering joining, please read our rules, to determine if this group is right for you:

http://www.meetup.com/Ladies-Who-Code-Washington-DC/about/


Gloria
